ience- we interview caregivers when developing new features- and then cycle-through the user testing process with individuals memory disorders. We can watch the emotions of users- gauging how the Therapal makes them feel when it is introduced to them- and when it responds with a friendly purr.</p><h4>Who is your idea designed for and how does it better support family caregivers as they care for a loved one with dementia?</h4><p>Therapalz makes smart therapeutic companion cats and dogs for individuals with memory disorders. The Therapal recreates the animal assisted therapy experience- providing the same experience as interacting with a real therapy cat or dog. To mimic the experience- the Therapal has a constant heartbeat- lifelike sounds- and responds to user interaction with a purr in both our cats and dogs. The Therapal acts an intervention for caregivers to regain control of the caregiving experience.</p><h4>How long has your idea existed?</h4><p>Over 1 year</p><h4>This idea emerged from</h4><p>A student collaboration</p>","2","This seems like a bizarre solution to caregivers of dementia patients and there are probably a lot more pressing concerns for that community than trying to setup a system to provide hundreds of smart comfort pets for dementia patients.","I don't know that robotic comfort pets is the smartest idea for patients with dementia. There are many other ways to calm down dementia patients and help caregivers who need stress relief, but this seems like a bizarre solution even if it's well intentioned.","It sounds fairly technical, involving smart technology and tech that might not be accessible to every caregiver. It also sounds like it might be expensive.","1","2","1"
